courses.learning_outcomes:
1) Equip students of public policy and administration with substantive knowledge on public policy concepts, models and processes;
2) Train students in the skill of public policy analysis through the use of specific techniques and case studies;
3) Raise students’ awareness of the challenges and opportunities they may face in their future decision-making careers.

courses.course_syllabus:
This course discusses how public policy-makers go about defining problems, assembling evidence, constructing alternatives, selecting criteria, projecting outcomes, confronting trade-offs and, finally, making public policy decisions. The course specifically reflects on global economic, social, environmental, technological and legal factors affecting public policy process and decisions. Each of these contextual factors is dealt with theoretically, using internationally recognized public policy texts and, practically, through climate change-related case studies as follows:

1) Economic factors and the deployment of the Green Climate Fund (GCF);
2) Social factors and climate justice;
3) Environmental factors and climate resilience to flooding in coastal cities;
4) Technological factors and the uptake of renewable energy;
5) Legal factors and the implementation of the Paris Agreement & its Rulebook.

courses.learning_outcomes:
(1) To understand the basic concepts of policy research;
(2) To comprehend social, political, economic and organizational factors which influence the research process;
(3) To acquire experiences in collecting and analyzing qualitative and quantitative information;
(4) To develop a research proposal on an actual policy issue;
(5) To relate research outcomes as inputs to policy formulation and implementation.

1) To demonstrate an awareness of the fact that the environment in which governments make policies and organise the society has substantially changed;
2) To understand the changing mechanisms for governing in the recent decade and the impacts they bring about;
3) To reflect on both local and international cases and consider how they can contribute to a better understanding of public policy and administration in Hong Kong; and
4) To identity governing problems in the world and how the shared experience can help combat common governing problems faced by different governments.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able:

1. To gain insight into the structure and functioning of the global financial system and its components;

2. To understand the underlying rationale for, scope of, and limitations of international and national (or equivalent) financial regulatory mechanisms.

1) To gain insights into the development of government relations strategies and examine the internal and external barriers and challenges when working across diverse industry sectors and jurisdictions;
2) To engage in facilitated discussion, enhanced by video and e-learning tools, to provide perspectives of operating at the frontline; and
3) To learn from theories as well as practical and real life case studies developed as learning tools.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1) Deepen the knowledge of the formulation of public policies and relevant political systems in Hong Kong;
2) Explore how good public policy formulation can be made;
3) Develop ability to evaluate the effectiveness of the public policy.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1) Acquire research writing skills under supervision of a teaching staff;
2) Master advanced concepts and major theories of the research topic;
3) Develop ability to manage independent research.
